{"cursor":"20885","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = United States Department of\nEnergy |type = Department |nativename = |nativename_a = |nativename_r = |logo =\n|logo_width = |logo_caption = |picture = US Dept of Energy Forrestal\nBuilding.jpg |picture_width = 140px |picture_caption = James Forrestal\nheadquarters complex in Washington, D.C. |seal = US-DeptOfEnergy-Seal.svg\n|seal_width = 140px |seal_caption = Seal of the Department of Energy |formed =\n|date1 = October 1, 1977 |date1_name = Activated |date2 = |date2_name =\n|preceding1 = Federal Energy Administration (FEA) |preceding2 = Energy Research\nand Development Administration (ERDA) |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction\n= |headquarters =1000 Independence Avenue SW, Washington D.C |coordinates =\n|employees = 16,000 federal (2009) [http://www.cfo.doe.gov/CF1-2/2008CR.pdf\n] 93,094 contract (2008) |budget = $30.6 billion (2012) |chief1_name\n= Dr. Steven Chu |chief1_position = Secretary |chief2_name = Daniel Poneman\n|chief2_position = Deputy Secretary. |parent_agency = |child1_agency =\n|child2_agency = |website = [http://www.energy.gov energy.gov] |footnotes = }}\nThe 'United States Department of Energy' ('DOE') is a Cabinet-level department\nof the United States government concerned with the United States' policies\nregarding energy and safety in handling nuclear material. Its responsibilities\ninclude the nation's nuclear weapons program, nuclear reactor production for the\nUnited States Navy, energy conservation, energy-related research, radioactive\nwaste disposal, and domestic energy production. It also directs research in\ngenomics; the Human Genome Project originated in a DOE initiative.\nDOE sponsors more research in the physical sciences than any other US federal\nagency; the majority of this research is conducted through its system\nof United States Department of Energy National Laboratories.\n\nThe agency is administered by the United States Secretary of Energy, and its\nheadquarters are located in southwest Washington, D.C., on Independence Avenue\nin the James V. Forrestal Building, named for James Forrestal, as well as in\nGermantown, Maryland.\n","linknr":659,"url":"United_States_Department_of_Energy","recorded":1362503499,"links":51,"instances":["law","southwest"],"pdf":["http://www.cfo.doe.gov/CF1-2/2008CR.pdf","http://www.ornl.gov/sci/techresources/Human_Genome/publicat/jmmbbag.pdf","http://www.ornl.gov/sci/techresources/Human_Genome/publicat/jmmbbag.pdf","http://www.cfo.doe.gov/budget/12budget/Content/FY2012Highlights.pdf","http://science.energy.gov/lpe/%E2%80%8Bstrategic-planning-process/~/media/lpe/pdf/FY_2011_Public_SC_Laboratory_Plans_2011-08-18.pdf"],"categories":["Nuclear weapons infrastructure of the United States|Department of Energy","Energy in the United States","United States Department of Energy|","Government agencies established in 1977","1977 establishments in the United States","United States federal executive departments|Energy"],"headings":["History","Organization","Facilities","Responsibility for nuclear weapons","Controversy","Related legislation","Budget","Energy Savings Performance Contract","Loan Guarantee Program","Energy Innovation Hubs","List of Secretaries of Energy","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/US-DeptOfEnergy-Seal.svg/140px-US-DeptOfEnergy-Seal.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/US_Dept_of_Energy_Forrestal_Building.jpg/140px-US_Dept_of_Energy_Forrestal_Building.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Department_of_Energy_Sign.jpg/220px-Department_of_Energy_Sign.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/DOE_org_chart_20111206.svg/300px-DOE_org_chart_20111206.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/